<p>Robert &#8220;Bob&#8221; Gordon, emeritus professor of philosophy at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, died this past April. <span id="more-54880"></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-54881 aligncenter" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/gordon-robert.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="266" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/gordon-robert.jpg 400w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/gordon-robert-300x200.jpg 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px" /></p>
<p>Professor Gordon was known for his work in philosophy of mind, cognitive science, and philosophy of the emotions, and in particular his development of <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/folkpsych-simulation/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">simulation theory</a>. He is the author of <em>The Structure of Emotions: Investigations in Cognitive Philosophy</em> (1987). You can learn more about his writings <a href="https://philpeople.org/profiles/robert-gordon" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>.</p>
<p>Gordon joined the Department of Philosophy at the University of Missouriâ€“St. Louis in 1970. He previously held positions at the University of Wisconsin and the the University of Florida. He earned his PhD from Columbia University and his undergraduate degree from Carleton College.</p>
<p>A celebration of the life of Professor Gordon will be taking place on Sunday, September 28, 2025, 5pm, at the Ethical Society of St. Louis (and <a href="https://wustl-hipaa.zoom.us/j/95104118463" target="_blank" rel="noopener">online</a>, as well).</p>
<p>Robert Gordon died on April 13, 2025.</p>
